        <section>
            <h2>Fundamental Rights (Articles 12-35)</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Article 14</strong>: Guarantees equality before the law and equal protection of the laws.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 19</strong>: Lists freedoms such as speech, assembly, and movement.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 21</strong>: Protects the right to life and personal liberty.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Directive Principles (Articles 36-51)</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Article 39</strong>: Directs the state to ensure equitable distribution of resources.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 44</strong>: Aims to secure a Uniform Civil Code for citizens.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 45</strong>: Provides for free and compulsory education for children under 14 years.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Structure of the Government</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Article 74</strong>: Establishes the Council of Ministers to aid and advise the President.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 124</strong>: Establishes the Supreme Court and details its composition and powers.</li>
                <li><strong>Article 280</strong>: Establishes the Finance Commission and outlines its duties.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

